00:01:44.187 --> 00:01:45.770
ARIANNA HUFFINGTON:
Thank you so much.

00:01:45.770 --> 00:01:54.050
I love having a fabulous Turkish
woman introduce a Greek woman

00:01:54.050 --> 00:01:58.160
with a massive accent compared
to her very subtle kind

00:01:58.160 --> 00:02:00.050
of little mysterious intonation.

00:02:00.050 --> 00:02:01.200
Where is she really from?

00:02:01.200 --> 00:02:04.129
With me, like is she Hungarian?

00:02:04.129 --> 00:02:04.670
Is she Greek?

00:02:04.670 --> 00:02:06.300
What is she?

00:02:06.300 --> 00:02:09.695
So I am delighted to be here.

00:02:09.695 --> 00:02:10.590
I love Google.

00:02:13.260 --> 00:02:14.970
I love everything you're doing.

00:02:14.970 --> 00:02:17.230
Including all your
wellness things,

00:02:17.230 --> 00:02:23.220
your sleep pods, your
obsession with running,

00:02:23.220 --> 00:02:25.320
your healthy snacks.

00:02:25.320 --> 00:02:26.162
But you're right.

00:02:26.162 --> 00:02:27.120
We'll talk about sleep.

00:02:27.120 --> 00:02:30.940
There's some improvement that
is needed in that department.

00:02:30.940 --> 00:02:34.860
But let's start with
the big picture.

00:02:34.860 --> 00:02:39.260
Greek philosophers used
to ask three questions.

00:02:39.260 --> 00:02:40.760
What do we need to know?

00:02:40.760 --> 00:02:43.020
That was before
Google, when you had

00:02:43.020 --> 00:02:45.970
to work hard to know things.

00:02:45.970 --> 00:02:48.770
How do we govern the city?

00:02:48.770 --> 00:02:52.150
And how do we live a good life?

00:02:52.150 --> 00:02:55.580
And somewhere in the
last two centuries

00:02:55.580 --> 00:02:58.740
we stopped asking
the last question.

00:02:58.740 --> 00:03:04.100
And the good life became
reduced to the successful life.

00:03:04.100 --> 00:03:08.710
And the successful life became
reduced to two metrics-- money

00:03:08.710 --> 00:03:09.325
and power.

00:03:09.325 --> 00:03:12.920
You know, slash
status, slash fame.

00:03:12.920 --> 00:03:17.420
And trying to live a life based
on just these two metrics,

00:03:17.420 --> 00:03:21.300
it's a little bit like trying
to sit on a two-legged stool.

00:03:21.300 --> 00:03:24.440
Sooner or later, you fall off.

00:03:24.440 --> 00:03:30.950
And that's why I wrote this
book to help us introduce

00:03:30.950 --> 00:03:32.960
in our lives the third metric.

00:03:32.960 --> 00:03:35.140
The third leg of the stool.

00:03:35.140 --> 00:03:38.580
So it's not about denying
the first two metrics.

00:03:38.580 --> 00:03:42.320
It's about adding a metric.

00:03:42.320 --> 00:03:48.480
And that metric of four
pillars is very simple.

00:03:48.480 --> 00:03:51.870
It starts with our
well-being in hand.

00:03:51.870 --> 00:03:55.950
Because without our
health and well-being,

00:03:55.950 --> 00:04:00.090
life is really not
the life we want.

00:04:00.090 --> 00:04:02.710
Sometimes we are
forced to deal with it,

00:04:02.710 --> 00:04:05.920
and with a lot of
lessons to be learned.

00:04:05.920 --> 00:04:09.590
But 75% of health care
problems and costs

00:04:09.590 --> 00:04:12.670
now are coming from
chronic preventable

00:04:12.670 --> 00:04:15.010
a stress-related diseases.

00:04:15.010 --> 00:04:18.140
So there's an element of health
and disease that we cannot

00:04:18.140 --> 00:04:19.370
control.

00:04:19.370 --> 00:04:21.550
But there's an awful
lot that we can control,

00:04:21.550 --> 00:04:23.860
and that we are kind of
bringing on ourselves

00:04:23.860 --> 00:04:26.010
in one way or another.

00:04:26.010 --> 00:04:29.790
Because as Philippe [INAUDIBLE],
the Belgian philosopher put it,

00:04:29.790 --> 00:04:34.370
burnout has become the
disease of our civilization.

00:04:34.370 --> 00:04:40.740
And in the course of succeeding,
we have sacrificed our health.

00:04:40.740 --> 00:04:44.060
Not perhaps when you are as
young as many of you here,

00:04:44.060 --> 00:04:47.670
but we see you know, people in
their 40s and 50s with heart

00:04:47.670 --> 00:04:50.860
disease, with the
high blood pressure.

00:04:50.860 --> 00:04:54.630
And then the growing
increase of mental diseases,

00:04:54.630 --> 00:04:57.410
of depression and anxiety.

00:04:57.410 --> 00:05:01.350
Right now, one in
six in the UK is

00:05:01.350 --> 00:05:04.820
suffering from some form
of depression or anxiety.

00:05:04.820 --> 00:05:06.430
One in six.

00:05:06.430 --> 00:05:09.120
So why, as a
civilization who've made

00:05:09.120 --> 00:05:15.810
incredible strides in a solving
a lot of social problems,

00:05:15.810 --> 00:05:18.200
and economic problems--
has a long way to go,

00:05:18.200 --> 00:05:21.970
but has made huge progress--
we have really barely scratched

00:05:21.970 --> 00:05:27.900
the surface of identifying
the inner causes of distress.

00:05:27.900 --> 00:05:31.490
And what is exciting right
now, because I'm an optimist.

00:05:31.490 --> 00:05:33.180
I'm a congenital optimist.

00:05:33.180 --> 00:05:35.940
Partly because I'm Greek.

00:05:35.940 --> 00:05:38.305
And partly because I'm
a naturalized American.

00:05:38.305 --> 00:05:43.710
So it's a kind of irresistible
combo of optimism.

00:05:43.710 --> 00:05:46.990
So my optimism comes
because right now we're

00:05:46.990 --> 00:05:50.250
living in a perfect storm,
where a lot of trends

00:05:50.250 --> 00:05:53.250
are converging to make
this an incredible moment

00:05:53.250 --> 00:05:56.550
for the cultural shifts
that you talked about.

00:05:56.550 --> 00:06:01.390
So the first trend is
the growing awareness

00:06:01.390 --> 00:06:07.790
of all of the incredible
impact of burnout.

00:06:07.790 --> 00:06:11.600
The second trend
is the new science

00:06:11.600 --> 00:06:16.080
that is validating ancient
wisdom about the importance

00:06:16.080 --> 00:06:21.740
of sleep, renewal, pauses in our
life to regenerate ourselves.

00:06:21.740 --> 00:06:26.600
All those things that have
been dismissed as unnecessary,

00:06:26.600 --> 00:06:28.800
all the language that
has been used, especially

00:06:28.800 --> 00:06:31.400
by men-- none of the men
here, because they're all

00:06:31.400 --> 00:06:36.160
enlightened-- but the men
who designed our world.

00:06:36.160 --> 00:06:38.430
That we'll sleep
when we're dead.

00:06:38.430 --> 00:06:41.740
Congratulating people
for working 24/7.

00:06:41.740 --> 00:06:46.990
All these things that have kind
of been part of our culture,

00:06:46.990 --> 00:06:50.750
that now we need to sort
of unravel and recognize

00:06:50.750 --> 00:06:52.290
that they are really a delusion.

00:06:52.290 --> 00:06:55.200
We now have a lot of science to
prove that they are a delusion.

00:06:55.200 --> 00:06:57.940
That in fact, taking care
of our human capital,

00:06:57.940 --> 00:07:00.470
nurturing ourselves,
unplugging and recharging

00:07:00.470 --> 00:07:03.690
our own performance
enhancement tools.

00:07:03.690 --> 00:07:07.300
They're not elements
of checking out.

00:07:07.300 --> 00:07:08.810
Far from it.

00:07:08.810 --> 00:07:12.710
They are the way to be most
effective and most creative.

00:07:12.710 --> 00:07:16.360
And the other trend is that
now more and more people

00:07:16.360 --> 00:07:18.460
are coming out of the closet.

00:07:18.460 --> 00:07:20.570
Not out of the
closet saying they

00:07:20.570 --> 00:07:22.230
are gay, although
that's happening too,

00:07:22.230 --> 00:07:24.290
and it's safer and safer.

00:07:24.290 --> 00:07:26.660
But coming out of the
closet and admitting

00:07:26.660 --> 00:07:29.090
that they are
meditators, that they're

00:07:29.090 --> 00:07:32.930
doing mindfulness courses,
and that they are actually

00:07:32.930 --> 00:07:35.280
introducing these
elements into their lives.

00:07:35.280 --> 00:07:40.000
And last year, 2013 was
the year when CEO after CEO

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:42.270
came out as being meditators.

00:07:42.270 --> 00:07:44.370
Marc Benioff of
Salesforce told us

00:07:44.370 --> 00:07:46.470
that he's been
meditating for 25 years.

00:07:46.470 --> 00:07:49.870
Ray Dalio, the CEO of
one of the biggest hedge

00:07:49.870 --> 00:07:53.610
funds, Bridgewater, said he's
been meditating for 35 years

00:07:53.610 --> 00:07:57.150
and described it as the
foundation of his success.

00:07:57.150 --> 00:08:02.010
So something happened where all
these things that before were

00:08:02.010 --> 00:08:07.460
seen as a little flaky, a little
new agey, a little California,

00:08:07.460 --> 00:08:11.370
are now seen as
safe to talk about,

00:08:11.370 --> 00:08:15.330
and in fact, scientifically
validated as a great way

00:08:15.330 --> 00:08:19.070
to lead and to
lead our own life.

00:08:19.070 --> 00:08:22.200
So all this is in
the first pillar

00:08:22.200 --> 00:08:24.090
of well-being and health.

00:08:24.090 --> 00:08:26.770
The second pillar is wisdom.

00:08:26.770 --> 00:08:30.590
You know, Google,
new technologies,

00:08:30.590 --> 00:08:35.380
have made it possible for us to
have literally unlimited data,

00:08:35.380 --> 00:08:37.640
to know everything.

00:08:37.640 --> 00:08:43.150
But you haven't yet made it
possible for us to find wisdom.

00:08:43.150 --> 00:08:48.040
And often, when
there's too much data,

00:08:48.040 --> 00:08:52.340
it's harder and harder to find
the needle in the haystack.

00:08:52.340 --> 00:08:55.480
So we need to tap
into our own wisdom.

00:08:55.480 --> 00:08:59.040
And that's where we need
to remember that we all

00:08:59.040 --> 00:09:03.380
have a place in us, which
is an incredible place

00:09:03.380 --> 00:09:08.670
of inner wisdom, inner
strength, in inner peace.

00:09:08.670 --> 00:09:13.390
But most of us don't live
there most of the time.

00:09:13.390 --> 00:09:16.570
Nobody lives there all the time.

00:09:16.570 --> 00:09:20.780
So life for me is a little bit
of a journey of how quickly can

00:09:20.780 --> 00:09:22.390
we course correct.

00:09:22.390 --> 00:09:26.250
How quickly can we
identify ourselves

00:09:26.250 --> 00:09:28.385
being off center and
return to center?

00:09:31.510 --> 00:09:35.070
If you think of it, we know
much more about our smartphones

00:09:35.070 --> 00:09:38.020
then we know about ourselves.

00:09:38.020 --> 00:09:40.340
We get alerts.

00:09:40.340 --> 00:09:42.750
20% battery remaining.

00:09:42.750 --> 00:09:45.340
17% battery remaining.

00:09:45.340 --> 00:09:48.460
By about 13%, we get
anxious and we look around

00:09:48.460 --> 00:09:50.867
for a recharging shrine.

00:09:50.867 --> 00:09:52.783
Lest something would
happen to our smartphone.

00:09:55.284 --> 00:09:56.950
We never say, you
know what, smartphone?

00:09:56.950 --> 00:09:57.400
Deal.

00:09:57.400 --> 00:09:57.899
OK?

00:09:57.899 --> 00:09:58.810
Just get through it.

00:10:03.990 --> 00:10:08.340
But we do say that to
ourselves all the time, right?

00:10:08.340 --> 00:10:12.080
And when I collapsed, I start
my book, and I'm so glad.

00:10:12.080 --> 00:10:14.870
Thank you so much for
getting copies for everybody.

00:10:14.870 --> 00:10:18.130
So you'll see I start my
book with this episode

00:10:18.130 --> 00:10:20.260
in my own life,
seven years ago when

00:10:20.260 --> 00:10:24.260
I collapsed from exhaustion,
burnout, and sleep deprivation.

00:10:24.260 --> 00:10:27.270
Hit my head on the way
down, broke my cheekbone,

00:10:27.270 --> 00:10:29.880
got four stitches
on my right eye.

00:10:29.880 --> 00:10:35.410
And as I look back, I must have
been below 0% battery remaining

00:10:35.410 --> 00:10:38.630
and I didn't even know it.

00:10:38.630 --> 00:10:41.500
I wasn't even aware of it.

00:10:41.500 --> 00:10:45.160
So increasing that awareness
about our own state

00:10:45.160 --> 00:10:49.170
of being makes it easier for us
to connect with our own wisdom,

00:10:49.170 --> 00:10:51.430
connect with our own strength.

00:10:51.430 --> 00:10:55.070
And let me just say,
this is important

00:10:55.070 --> 00:10:58.920
whether you're at the
top of the world managing

00:10:58.920 --> 00:11:01.520
multiple demands on
your time and attention,

00:11:01.520 --> 00:11:03.985
or whether you're
just starting in life,

00:11:03.985 --> 00:11:06.990
or whether you're struggling to
put food on the table, wherever

00:11:06.990 --> 00:11:10.720
you are in life, when we
connect with that place, that's

00:11:10.720 --> 00:11:13.500
when we connect
with our resilience.

00:11:13.500 --> 00:11:17.790
And after all, whether you
succeed in life, in the bigger

00:11:17.790 --> 00:11:19.550
sense of the word
or not, depends

00:11:19.550 --> 00:11:23.050
on how easily
you're discouraged.

00:11:23.050 --> 00:11:25.450
Because everybody has
failed along the way.

00:11:25.450 --> 00:11:28.690
I have an entire
speech on my failures,

00:11:28.690 --> 00:11:30.510
if you want to hear it.

00:11:30.510 --> 00:11:33.800
Because very often when
people look at your success,

00:11:33.800 --> 00:11:36.880
they don't know how many times
you failed along the way,

00:11:36.880 --> 00:11:39.140
and I think that's
terribly unfortunate.

00:11:39.140 --> 00:11:41.255
Because young people--
and I have two daughters

00:11:41.255 --> 00:11:45.580
in their twenties-- need
to know that failure is not

00:11:45.580 --> 00:11:46.700
the opposite of success.

00:11:46.700 --> 00:11:49.380
It's a stepping
stone to success.

00:11:49.380 --> 00:11:51.550
But what makes it
possible to accept

00:11:51.550 --> 00:11:55.735
that is the fact that you
have your own resilience,

00:11:55.735 --> 00:12:00.160
your own strength and peace
and wisdom that you tap into.

00:12:00.160 --> 00:12:02.290
So that you're
not just dependent

00:12:02.290 --> 00:12:06.470
on the outside
circumstances of your life.

00:12:06.470 --> 00:12:11.660
One of the enemies of finding
our wisdom is multitasking.

00:12:11.660 --> 00:12:15.320
And everybody here in
this room, including me

00:12:15.320 --> 00:12:19.610
has really been brought
up in a new era thinking

00:12:19.610 --> 00:12:23.060
that multitasking
enhances our productivity.

00:12:23.060 --> 00:12:26.400
So I know you
Googlers love data.

00:12:26.400 --> 00:12:30.100
So please look at the 45
pages of scientific endnotes

00:12:30.100 --> 00:12:31.550
at the end of the book.

00:12:31.550 --> 00:12:35.180
I put them there for you.

00:12:35.180 --> 00:12:37.500
You don't have to believe
anything I'm saying.

00:12:37.500 --> 00:12:38.690
Just look at the data.

00:12:38.690 --> 00:12:40.910
There is no such
thing as multitasking.

00:12:40.910 --> 00:12:42.040
It's task switching.

00:12:42.040 --> 00:12:44.170
It's the most stressful
thing you can do.

00:12:44.170 --> 00:12:48.680
And it robs you of the
ability to experience

00:12:48.680 --> 00:12:52.600
that third dimension of wonder.

00:12:52.600 --> 00:12:57.590
Because you know, life
is an incredible mystery.

00:12:57.590 --> 00:12:59.440
And being connected
with the fact

00:12:59.440 --> 00:13:01.570
that we're living in
an incredible mystery

00:13:01.570 --> 00:13:06.540
is so important for
bringing joy into our lives.

00:13:06.540 --> 00:13:08.760
And multitasking is
the enemy of that.

00:13:08.760 --> 00:13:10.250
I live in New York.

00:13:10.250 --> 00:13:12.830
And walking down the
streets of New York now,

00:13:12.830 --> 00:13:16.440
you hardly see anybody who
is not either on the phone,

00:13:16.440 --> 00:13:19.890
or worse, texting while walking.

00:13:19.890 --> 00:13:22.340
And texting while
walking is seen

00:13:22.340 --> 00:13:24.150
as a kind of badge
of importance.

00:13:24.150 --> 00:13:27.020
Because you are so
important and so busy,

00:13:27.020 --> 00:13:30.190
that you cannot just walk.

00:13:30.190 --> 00:13:32.340
And so less important
and less busy

00:13:32.340 --> 00:13:35.110
people need to get
out of your way.

00:13:35.110 --> 00:13:39.280
Because they are
obviously just walking.

00:13:39.280 --> 00:13:43.510
When I stopped multitasking
while I was walking,

00:13:43.510 --> 00:13:46.890
I started noticing things
that I had not noticed before.

00:13:46.890 --> 00:13:50.110
Next to my apartment there
is this beautiful building

00:13:50.110 --> 00:13:51.890
with this incredible
ornamentation

00:13:51.890 --> 00:13:53.350
at the top, which
I had never seen.

00:13:53.350 --> 00:13:55.433
And I asked a friend, I
said, when did this go up?

00:13:55.433 --> 00:14:00.960
And she said, 1890.

00:14:00.960 --> 00:14:06.010
So what else are we missing
when we are constantly

00:14:06.010 --> 00:14:10.640
buried either in our thoughts
or in our smartphones?

00:14:10.640 --> 00:14:13.300
And being buried in our
thoughts is another issue

00:14:13.300 --> 00:14:15.950
that we need to deal with.

00:14:15.950 --> 00:14:19.300
That's what the whole
mindfulness practice is about.

00:14:19.300 --> 00:14:22.060
It's about being
present right here.

00:14:22.060 --> 00:14:24.860
Rather than lost
in our thoughts,

00:14:24.860 --> 00:14:29.350
which are often either
judging us about what we did,

00:14:29.350 --> 00:14:35.570
or judging somebody else, or
worrying about what's coming.

00:14:35.570 --> 00:14:39.550
And our body-- again,
look at the science--

00:14:39.550 --> 00:14:44.330
does not distinguish between
real things going wrong,

00:14:44.330 --> 00:14:47.240
and our imagination and
our thoughts about things

00:14:47.240 --> 00:14:47.950
going wrong.

00:14:47.950 --> 00:14:49.800
As Montaigne, the
French philosopher

00:14:49.800 --> 00:14:53.670
put it-- there were many
terrible things in my life,

00:14:53.670 --> 00:14:57.842
but most of them never happened.

00:14:57.842 --> 00:14:59.550
These are the kind of
negative fantasies.

00:14:59.550 --> 00:15:04.240
I tell my daughters, never
lose in your own fantasies.

00:15:04.240 --> 00:15:06.765
They're yours, make them good.

00:15:06.765 --> 00:15:09.110
You know, don't
imagine the worst.

00:15:09.110 --> 00:15:11.410
Incidentally, I don't
believe at all the idea that

00:15:11.410 --> 00:15:13.620
imagine the worst because
if prepares you for it.

00:15:13.620 --> 00:15:15.910
I don't believe that at all.

00:15:15.910 --> 00:15:19.180
Because when
something bad happens,

00:15:19.180 --> 00:15:23.210
and it happens in all our
lives, we are in a position

00:15:23.210 --> 00:15:25.200
to deal with because
we are fully present.

00:15:25.200 --> 00:15:28.020
Our mind, our emotions,
and our body in one place.

00:15:28.020 --> 00:15:30.160
You can not deal
with something bad

00:15:30.160 --> 00:15:33.260
when it hasn't happened yet,
except by stressing yourself

00:15:33.260 --> 00:15:35.460
out.

00:15:35.460 --> 00:15:38.610
And it's amazing just
reading the science

00:15:38.610 --> 00:15:43.520
around how animals operate.

00:15:43.520 --> 00:15:45.950
Gazelles are my screen saver.

00:15:45.950 --> 00:15:48.250
They are kind of a
role model for me.

00:15:48.250 --> 00:15:52.800
Because gazelles
really run really hard

00:15:52.800 --> 00:15:54.910
when there's a danger.

00:15:54.910 --> 00:15:59.100
When there's a lion or
a leopard chasing them.

00:15:59.100 --> 00:16:02.870
But the minute the danger
passes, they graze.

00:16:02.870 --> 00:16:07.060
And there's absolutely zero
stress in their system.

00:16:07.060 --> 00:16:10.640
So that's really my
ideal state of being.

00:16:10.640 --> 00:16:12.660
The equivalent for
us running hard

00:16:12.660 --> 00:16:14.420
is we have a big
project to complete,

00:16:14.420 --> 00:16:16.630
we have something to do.

00:16:16.630 --> 00:16:18.590
We put 100% into it.

00:16:18.590 --> 00:16:19.990
Then it's done.

00:16:19.990 --> 00:16:25.330
But we keep staying in
a fight or flight mode.

00:16:25.330 --> 00:16:27.050
And that's what
we need to change,

00:16:27.050 --> 00:16:30.740
because we need to give
ourselves recovery time.

00:16:30.740 --> 00:16:36.190
How healthy we are depends on
how much recovery opportunity

00:16:36.190 --> 00:16:37.250
we give to our system.

00:16:39.840 --> 00:16:45.920
And every religion and
every major philosopher

00:16:45.920 --> 00:16:49.090
really talks in different
language about these pauses.

00:16:49.090 --> 00:16:53.970
Those of you who have started
Japanese philosophy, zen,

00:16:53.970 --> 00:16:56.940
or Japanese art, is
the concept of ma,

00:16:56.940 --> 00:16:59.290
which literally means space.

00:16:59.290 --> 00:17:00.780
And it's something sacred.

00:17:00.780 --> 00:17:03.750
You know, bringing
space into your life,

00:17:03.750 --> 00:17:06.869
pauses into your life,
the whole tea ritual,

00:17:06.869 --> 00:17:10.550
whether in England, or much
more neutralized in Japan,

00:17:10.550 --> 00:17:13.670
is about pausing.

00:17:13.670 --> 00:17:17.109
And related to that
now is something

00:17:17.109 --> 00:17:18.635
that we are all
engaged in, which

00:17:18.635 --> 00:17:21.099
is innovation and creativity.

00:17:21.099 --> 00:17:22.859
This is really
the supreme irony,

00:17:22.859 --> 00:17:27.540
that our culture worships
innovation and creativity,

00:17:27.540 --> 00:17:29.780
but we all live in a
way that completely

00:17:29.780 --> 00:17:32.940
kills both of these things.

00:17:32.940 --> 00:17:37.620
Because there's nothing worse
for innovation and creativity

00:17:37.620 --> 00:17:41.050
then being perpetually
connected to our devices.

00:17:41.050 --> 00:17:46.630
Because we're at the mercy of
incoming, what's coming at us.

00:17:46.630 --> 00:17:50.780
So if you look at some
of the major discoveries,

00:17:50.780 --> 00:17:56.080
whether it's Archimedes
while having a bath,

00:17:56.080 --> 00:17:59.010
coming out and
shouting, Eureka .

00:17:59.010 --> 00:18:02.460
And getting out naked, screaming
that he found his major love,

00:18:02.460 --> 00:18:05.125
which would have been a great
tweetable moment, right?

00:18:07.940 --> 00:18:09.810
You could just
imagine the retweets.

00:18:09.810 --> 00:18:15.610
It would've been better
than Miley Cyrus twerking.

00:18:15.610 --> 00:18:19.970
Or Newton, in a contemplative
mood in his garden,

00:18:19.970 --> 00:18:23.470
and suddenly the apple falls.

00:18:23.470 --> 00:18:25.960
And there's a lot of
literature about the fact

00:18:25.960 --> 00:18:28.320
that he was in a
contemplative mood.

00:18:28.320 --> 00:18:30.050
And when you saw
that apple falling,

00:18:30.050 --> 00:18:32.560
he suddenly thought, why
is this all coming down

00:18:32.560 --> 00:18:34.240
in a perpendicular way?

00:18:34.240 --> 00:18:37.560
And the law of gravity was born.

00:18:37.560 --> 00:18:42.620
So for those of us who worship
creativity and innovation,

00:18:42.620 --> 00:18:47.020
we need to realize that time
famine, and time pressure,

00:18:47.020 --> 00:18:51.290
and burnout really
are killing them.

00:18:51.290 --> 00:18:57.050
And when we look at the
history of startups,

00:18:57.050 --> 00:19:00.680
we know that startup
entrepreneurs are notoriously

00:19:00.680 --> 00:19:03.220
sleep deprived and burning
the candle at both ends.

00:19:03.220 --> 00:19:05.620
And we assume this
is the way to do it.

00:19:05.620 --> 00:19:09.330
But then why do 3/4
of startups fail?

00:19:09.330 --> 00:19:11.110
Maybe somebody here
should do a study

00:19:11.110 --> 00:19:14.410
about the correlation between
sleep deprivation and startup

00:19:14.410 --> 00:19:16.010
failures.

00:19:16.010 --> 00:19:20.210
Because we really
need new role models,

00:19:20.210 --> 00:19:26.260
and we need ruthlessly
to provide the evidence,

00:19:26.260 --> 00:19:31.740
to eliminate the delusion, that
burnout is the way to succeed.

00:19:31.740 --> 00:19:35.200
And I'm constantly in
search of new role models.

00:19:35.200 --> 00:19:38.060
One of my favorites
is actually a woman.

00:19:38.060 --> 00:19:41.210
Padmasree Warrior, who
is the chief technology

00:19:41.210 --> 00:19:43.140
officer of Cisco.

00:19:43.140 --> 00:19:46.280
And she oversees 10s of
thousands of engineers.

00:19:46.280 --> 00:19:48.470
And she spoke at our
Thrive conference.

00:19:48.470 --> 00:19:51.720
And she said, I sleep
for eight hours.

00:19:51.720 --> 00:19:53.260
I meditate.

00:19:53.260 --> 00:19:55.100
I write haikus.

00:19:55.100 --> 00:19:56.830
I paint.

00:19:56.830 --> 00:20:01.420
And every Saturday I
do a digital detox.

00:20:01.420 --> 00:20:05.650
And she has a great role
model herself, which is God.

00:20:05.650 --> 00:20:08.830
He worked very hard for six
days, created heaven and earth,

00:20:08.830 --> 00:20:11.600
and he took a day off.

00:20:11.600 --> 00:20:13.800
That's like, he did
a pretty awesome job.

00:20:13.800 --> 00:20:16.160
I mean, there are few
imperfections here and there.

00:20:16.160 --> 00:20:18.350
We're still in the better stage.

00:20:18.350 --> 00:20:24.470
But nevertheless, this
is not just a fairy tale.

00:20:24.470 --> 00:20:30.420
This is a very significant
story about the importance

00:20:30.420 --> 00:20:30.920
of renewal.

00:20:33.440 --> 00:20:39.180
And the final pillar,
well-being, wisdom, wonder,

00:20:39.180 --> 00:20:41.380
is giving.

00:20:41.380 --> 00:20:46.500
Because our culture
celebrates go-getters.

00:20:46.500 --> 00:20:50.280
And very occasionally
celebrates go-givers.

00:20:50.280 --> 00:20:56.360
We celebrate them around
Christmas and the holidays.

00:20:56.360 --> 00:20:59.100
But in fact, we now
have the science

00:20:59.100 --> 00:21:03.710
that shows that our genes
are wired for giving.

00:21:03.710 --> 00:21:10.270
And when we give, all of the
inflammatory markers of disease

00:21:10.270 --> 00:21:11.940
go down.

00:21:11.940 --> 00:21:16.250
And giving is basically
a shortcut to happiness.

00:21:16.250 --> 00:21:18.690
And there's great
neuroscientific evidence

00:21:18.690 --> 00:21:22.490
out of the University of
Wisconsin about this, and about

00:21:22.490 --> 00:21:24.780
the fact that happiness
is a learned skill.

00:21:24.780 --> 00:21:25.800
Did you know that?

00:21:25.800 --> 00:21:27.880
That you can learn to be happy?

00:21:27.880 --> 00:21:29.880
We all think we can
learn to play tennis.

00:21:29.880 --> 00:21:31.130
We can learn to play golf.

00:21:31.130 --> 00:21:32.130
Whatever.

00:21:32.130 --> 00:21:37.510
But we don't realize that
we also learn to be happy.

00:21:37.510 --> 00:21:40.110
And the Greek word
for happiness,

00:21:40.110 --> 00:21:43.030
in its most profound
sense, is [SPEAKING GREEK],

00:21:43.030 --> 00:21:45.650
which translated
would mean thriving,

00:21:45.650 --> 00:21:47.510
which is why I picked that word.

00:21:47.510 --> 00:21:49.540
But in a literal
sense, it means--

00:21:49.540 --> 00:21:52.880
and we have a fellow Greek
here who can correct me--

00:21:52.880 --> 00:21:57.620
it means basically being at
peace with your own demons.

00:21:57.620 --> 00:22:01.060
Because the Greeks realized that
ultimately, happiness is not

00:22:01.060 --> 00:22:03.620
a function of external
circumstances,

00:22:03.620 --> 00:22:06.390
It's a function of
our inner harmony,

00:22:06.390 --> 00:22:09.310
with our external circumstances.

00:22:09.310 --> 00:22:12.040
And some people are
infinitely dissatisfied,

00:22:12.040 --> 00:22:13.990
no matter what they have.

00:22:13.990 --> 00:22:16.320
Because somebody
else may have more,

00:22:16.320 --> 00:22:18.710
somebody else always has more.

00:22:18.710 --> 00:22:21.710
If you value your life just
in terms of these two metrics,

00:22:21.710 --> 00:22:25.560
there is always
going to be somebody

00:22:25.560 --> 00:22:28.260
who is beating you at the game.

00:22:28.260 --> 00:22:31.670
I like to quote Mikhail
Baryshinikov, who said,

00:22:31.670 --> 00:22:36.800
I don't try to dance
better than anyone else.

00:22:36.800 --> 00:22:40.430
I just try to dance
better than myself.

00:22:40.430 --> 00:22:42.480
And I think it's really
great whether you're

00:22:42.480 --> 00:22:46.770
looking at your life, or
you're looking at your company.

00:22:46.770 --> 00:22:50.820
At the Huffington Post, I tell
everybody, the most important

00:22:50.820 --> 00:22:54.390
thing is for us to keep
disrupting ourselves.

00:22:54.390 --> 00:22:56.150
To keep innovating.

00:22:56.150 --> 00:22:59.240
It's not about what
anybody else is doing.

00:22:59.240 --> 00:23:02.240
We're not competing
against anyone else.

00:23:02.240 --> 00:23:06.600
And that is an incredibly
liberating way to look at life.

00:23:06.600 --> 00:23:13.180
And I would love to see giving
time, volunteering, be part

00:23:13.180 --> 00:23:16.540
of the way that we bring up
children from an early age.

00:23:16.540 --> 00:23:20.310
Because I've seen the difference
it makes to my children

00:23:20.310 --> 00:23:23.080
when they were young
and I had more control

00:23:23.080 --> 00:23:24.770
over what they were doing.

00:23:24.770 --> 00:23:28.200
And I would take them to
volunteer at places of art

00:23:28.200 --> 00:23:31.930
with children, where
they could see and be

00:23:31.930 --> 00:23:34.600
in touch with the suffering
in the world, which would make

00:23:34.600 --> 00:23:38.400
them much less narcissistic,
and much less preoccupied

00:23:38.400 --> 00:23:40.680
with everything
happening in their lives.

00:23:40.680 --> 00:23:46.360
So these are the four
pillars of the third metric.

00:23:46.360 --> 00:23:50.050
And because I very
much want the book

00:23:50.050 --> 00:23:53.720
to be a bridge between knowing
what we should be doing

00:23:53.720 --> 00:23:57.920
and actually doing it, I
have 12 steps in the book.

00:23:57.920 --> 00:23:59.910
I picked 12
deliberately, because we

00:23:59.910 --> 00:24:02.760
are addicted to our
current way of life.

00:24:02.760 --> 00:24:05.850
12 steps, and you can pick
one step to start with,

00:24:05.850 --> 00:24:08.320
whichever resonates
with you, to begin

00:24:08.320 --> 00:24:11.260
to bring these
changes in your life.

00:24:11.260 --> 00:24:15.100
And my first step was sleep.

00:24:15.100 --> 00:24:19.370
I went from four to five
hours to seven to eight hours.

00:24:19.370 --> 00:24:21.690
And as you said,
sleep deprivation

00:24:21.690 --> 00:24:24.120
is being worn at the moment
like a badge of honor

00:24:24.120 --> 00:24:25.900
by many people.

00:24:25.900 --> 00:24:29.920
I had dinner recently with a
guy who bragged that he had only

00:24:29.920 --> 00:24:32.489
gotten four hours
sleep the night before.

00:24:32.489 --> 00:24:34.280
And I thought to myself--
I didn't say it--

00:24:34.280 --> 00:24:36.080
but I thought to
myself, you know what?

00:24:36.080 --> 00:24:37.556
If you had gotten
five, this dinner

00:24:37.556 --> 00:24:39.180
would have been a
lot more interesting.

00:24:45.040 --> 00:24:48.790
But we are all
operating from the sense

00:24:48.790 --> 00:24:52.470
of time famine-- you
know, breathlessness.

00:24:52.470 --> 00:24:56.440
A feeling that we just don't
have enough time to sleep.

00:24:56.440 --> 00:24:59.470
I really just want
everybody to carefully look

00:24:59.470 --> 00:25:02.820
at their discretionary time.

00:25:02.820 --> 00:25:06.100
People have much more
discretionary time

00:25:06.100 --> 00:25:12.170
that they think Somebody's
watching "House of Cards."

00:25:12.170 --> 00:25:16.660
And that's why I really believe
in finding a thrive buddy.

00:25:16.660 --> 00:25:20.430
Finding somebody in your
life who can support you,

00:25:20.430 --> 00:25:25.800
and you can support them as
you are introducing new habits.

00:25:25.800 --> 00:25:30.452
And let's say you are tempted
to binge watch "House of Cards"

00:25:30.452 --> 00:25:31.910
at night instead
of going to sleep,

00:25:31.910 --> 00:25:34.368
you can call your thrive buddy,
and they can cool you down.

00:25:34.368 --> 00:25:37.310
They can tell you to
just take a deep breath,

00:25:37.310 --> 00:25:40.780
and close your laptop, and you
can watch it over the weekend.

00:25:40.780 --> 00:25:45.290
Because the point is that if
you don't get enough sleep--

00:25:45.290 --> 00:25:49.430
you know that feeling of
being tired and walking around

00:25:49.430 --> 00:25:50.720
like a zombie during the day?

00:25:50.720 --> 00:25:52.660
I now really hate that feeling.

00:25:52.660 --> 00:25:54.625
How many people are
sleep deprived today?

00:25:58.620 --> 00:25:59.120
OK.

00:25:59.120 --> 00:26:00.065
You don't have to be.

00:26:00.065 --> 00:26:01.523
It's just a matter
of prioritizing.

00:26:04.330 --> 00:26:05.980
Whatever it takes
to recharge you.

00:26:05.980 --> 00:26:08.620
And how much sleep you
need is individual.

00:26:08.620 --> 00:26:11.030
Most people need eight hours.

00:26:11.030 --> 00:26:12.250
But whatever you need.

00:26:12.250 --> 00:26:13.809
You know how you know it?

00:26:13.809 --> 00:26:15.350
Because you wake up
without an alarm.

00:26:17.980 --> 00:26:23.350
And another very important
step is at the end of the day,

00:26:23.350 --> 00:26:27.850
turn off all your devices
and gently escort them out

00:26:27.850 --> 00:26:30.350
of your bedroom.

00:26:30.350 --> 00:26:31.950
Very important.

00:26:31.950 --> 00:26:34.470
Because otherwise
you'll wake up and be

00:26:34.470 --> 00:26:37.310
tempted to look at your data
if your smartphone is charging

00:26:37.310 --> 00:26:38.320
by your bed.

00:26:38.320 --> 00:26:40.980
And I know all your excuses.

00:26:40.980 --> 00:26:46.110
Like, I need my smartphone
because it's my alarm clock.

00:26:46.110 --> 00:26:46.680
OK.

00:26:46.680 --> 00:26:48.915
First of all, if you put
it in the room next door,

00:26:48.915 --> 00:26:49.900
you can still hear it.

00:26:49.900 --> 00:26:54.720
Or you get a nice
vintage-looking alarm clock.

00:26:54.720 --> 00:26:56.880
In the states, I give
them to all my friends

00:26:56.880 --> 00:26:57.770
from Pottery Barn.

00:26:57.770 --> 00:27:00.020
They're $32.

00:27:00.020 --> 00:27:01.760
I'm sure you can find them here.

00:27:01.760 --> 00:27:05.694
I think David Jones, I was
told, and Selfridges have them.

00:27:05.694 --> 00:27:07.610
John, we should do a
little research for that,

00:27:07.610 --> 00:27:11.190
so that we can advocate
where you can go and get it.

00:27:11.190 --> 00:27:17.390
The point is don't allow
yourself to be tempted.

00:27:17.390 --> 00:27:19.470
And I'm only going to
mention one more step that

00:27:19.470 --> 00:27:25.570
was important to me, which
is at the end of the day,

00:27:25.570 --> 00:27:31.180
scan your day and look at
something that you can drop.

00:27:31.180 --> 00:27:32.780
That no longer serves you.

00:27:32.780 --> 00:27:38.400
It could be a grudge,
a resentment, anger.

00:27:38.400 --> 00:27:39.690
Just something.

00:27:39.690 --> 00:27:42.040
Or it could be a
project that you thought

00:27:42.040 --> 00:27:48.610
you were going to do, but
really you're not going to.

00:27:48.610 --> 00:27:50.540
The latest project
that I've dropped

00:27:50.540 --> 00:27:54.170
was becoming a good skier.

00:27:54.170 --> 00:27:56.370
I decided that really
I was not going

00:27:56.370 --> 00:27:59.660
to invest time and energy
into becoming a good skier.

00:27:59.660 --> 00:28:02.450
And it was very
liberating to realize

00:28:02.450 --> 00:28:05.225
that I could complete the
project by dropping it.

00:28:08.720 --> 00:28:12.860
So as far as I'm
concerned, skiing is done.

00:28:12.860 --> 00:28:16.475
When I go skiing with my
daughters or with friends now,

00:28:16.475 --> 00:28:18.600
they ski, and I sit by the fire.

00:28:18.600 --> 00:28:21.010
I drink hot chocolate,
and I read a good book.

00:28:21.010 --> 00:28:23.380
And I'm very happy.

00:28:23.380 --> 00:28:25.840
So just see what is it that
you're not really going to do.

00:28:25.840 --> 00:28:28.740
And then you can really
invest your time and energy

00:28:28.740 --> 00:28:31.890
into the things you
are going to do.

00:28:31.890 --> 00:28:34.720
So let me wrap up so
that we can leave plenty

00:28:34.720 --> 00:28:37.110
of time for questions by
saying that if we're alike,

00:28:37.110 --> 00:28:40.970
you have 30,000 days to
play the game of life.

00:28:40.970 --> 00:28:44.700
How we play depends
on what we value.

00:28:44.700 --> 00:28:48.630
And if we only value
the first two metrics,

00:28:48.630 --> 00:28:53.090
we're never really going to be
thriving, because we're always

00:28:53.090 --> 00:28:56.500
going to be putting our life
on hold until we accomplish

00:28:56.500 --> 00:28:57.236
something.

00:28:57.236 --> 00:28:58.860
And then as soon as
we accomplish that,

00:28:58.860 --> 00:29:00.520
we'll have another
goal, and we're

00:29:00.520 --> 00:29:02.950
going to be putting
our life on hold again.

00:29:02.950 --> 00:29:05.120
And basically we'll
be shrinking ourselves

00:29:05.120 --> 00:29:08.460
down to our jobs
and our to-do lists.

00:29:08.460 --> 00:29:11.260
And I just did an
interview with Oprah,

00:29:11.260 --> 00:29:13.950
and she asks everybody the
same question at the end.

00:29:13.950 --> 00:29:16.340
What do you know for sure?

00:29:16.340 --> 00:29:19.150
And I said to her,
what I know for sure is

00:29:19.150 --> 00:29:22.170
that however magnificent
your job is Oprah,

00:29:22.170 --> 00:29:27.050
or however great my job is, or
however great anybody's job is,

00:29:27.050 --> 00:29:30.820
who we are in our essence
is more magnificent.

00:29:30.820 --> 00:29:32.470
We are more than our jobs.

00:29:35.270 --> 00:29:39.090
And if you need
reinforcement of that,

00:29:39.090 --> 00:29:41.610
just remember the last time
you were at a memorial service,

00:29:41.610 --> 00:29:42.860
listening to a eulogy.

00:29:42.860 --> 00:29:47.690
You know, our eulogies are very
different from our resumes.

00:29:47.690 --> 00:29:49.570
Have you ever heard a
eulogy where they said,

00:29:49.570 --> 00:29:50.785
George was amazing.

00:29:50.785 --> 00:29:53.478
He increased market
share by one third.

00:29:56.410 --> 00:30:03.670
So when we remember
all that, then we

00:30:03.670 --> 00:30:07.880
can really find that place
that Archimedes called,

00:30:07.880 --> 00:30:10.610
give me a place to stand,
and I can move the world.

00:30:10.610 --> 00:30:12.630
We all have that place.

00:30:12.630 --> 00:30:17.100
You know, we call it being in
the zone, being in the flow.

00:30:17.100 --> 00:30:19.020
So we find that place.

00:30:19.020 --> 00:30:22.470
And from that place
we live our lives

00:30:22.470 --> 00:30:27.600
with more gratitude, more
creativity, more joy,

00:30:27.600 --> 00:30:29.590
and yes, more sleep.

00:30:29.590 --> 00:30:30.250
Thank you.

00:30:42.400 --> 00:30:45.220
