00:31:24.996 --> 00:31:26.280
That would be really great.

00:31:26.280 --> 00:31:28.570
But normally, I get
eight hours, because I

00:31:28.570 --> 00:31:29.760
am a huge fan of sleep.

00:31:29.760 --> 00:31:34.630
I really, totally agree
with what you're saying.

00:31:34.630 --> 00:31:38.040
What I would really like to
understand from you is actually

00:31:38.040 --> 00:31:40.350
as a working mom
yourself, if you

00:31:40.350 --> 00:31:45.717
could have spoken to yourself
kind of, 15, 18 years ago

00:31:45.717 --> 00:31:47.300
when your children
were really little,

00:31:47.300 --> 00:31:49.430
what do you think you
would do differently?

00:31:49.430 --> 00:31:51.570
And have you got any
advice for the working

00:31:51.570 --> 00:31:52.600
parents in the room?

00:31:52.600 --> 00:31:54.799
Because I think it's
not just a woman's role.

00:31:54.799 --> 00:31:56.090
ARIANNA HUFFINGTON: Absolutely.

00:31:56.090 --> 00:31:57.310
That's a great question.

00:31:57.310 --> 00:32:00.530
And so what I would
have done differently

00:32:00.530 --> 00:32:04.590
is to be fully present
for my children.

00:32:04.590 --> 00:32:10.720
Because when I look back,
I never missed a milestone.

00:32:10.720 --> 00:32:14.745
You know, a performance,
or any school event,

00:32:14.745 --> 00:32:17.370
although I never
baked the cookies.

00:32:17.370 --> 00:32:20.550
And it's perfectly OK not
to bake the cookies, just

00:32:20.550 --> 00:32:22.460
in case you are
guilty about that.

00:32:22.460 --> 00:32:25.280
Because I really think when
they take the baby out,

00:32:25.280 --> 00:32:26.870
they put the guilt in.

00:32:26.870 --> 00:32:31.690
And every working
mother I know is guilty,

00:32:31.690 --> 00:32:33.690
that she's not doing a good job.

00:32:33.690 --> 00:32:39.380
So I would just
basically by practicing

00:32:39.380 --> 00:32:43.610
the things I'm talking about
now, being recharged myself,

00:32:43.610 --> 00:32:45.620
I would have been able
to be fully present,

00:32:45.620 --> 00:32:48.220
instead of being
with them physically,

00:32:48.220 --> 00:32:50.440
but my mind being
somewhere else.

00:32:50.440 --> 00:32:53.445
Like, on what I was going to do
tomorrow, or what I didn't do,

00:32:53.445 --> 00:32:55.850
or my completions, et cetera.

00:32:55.850 --> 00:33:00.230
So that that's my
biggest advice.

00:33:00.230 --> 00:33:02.980
And because I really think
that we miss so much.

00:33:02.980 --> 00:33:06.070
And these are such
special years.

00:33:06.070 --> 00:33:08.495
And even though,
I'm sure there are

00:33:08.495 --> 00:33:10.810
times when your one-year-old
wakes you up at night.

00:33:10.810 --> 00:33:13.300
It's just unbelievably adorable.

00:33:13.300 --> 00:33:15.596
And there will be times
later in your life

00:33:15.596 --> 00:33:16.970
when you would
like to spend more

00:33:16.970 --> 00:33:19.890
time with that one-year-old,
but-- is it a boy or girl?

00:33:19.890 --> 00:33:20.629
AUDIENCE: Girl.

00:33:20.629 --> 00:33:22.670
ARIANNA HUFFINGTON: But
she will be awfully busy.

00:33:22.670 --> 00:33:25.320
So treasure every moment.

00:33:25.320 --> 00:33:27.450
And it's not easy.

00:33:27.450 --> 00:33:28.390
No question about it.

00:33:28.390 --> 00:33:31.640
That's why I'm a big
believer in naps.

00:33:31.640 --> 00:33:33.840
And I'm glad you
have nap pods here.

00:33:33.840 --> 00:33:34.670
Use them.

00:33:34.670 --> 00:33:35.690
Use them liberally.

00:33:35.690 --> 00:33:37.650
Because a 20 minute
nap, if you've

00:33:37.650 --> 00:33:41.140
had a disruptive night of
sleep because of a young child,

00:33:41.140 --> 00:33:44.440
or a sick toddler.

00:33:44.440 --> 00:33:48.910
But a 20 minute nap, as
Winston Churchill famously

00:33:48.910 --> 00:33:51.250
proved by calling
them power naps,

00:33:51.250 --> 00:33:52.770
having them
regularly and winning

00:33:52.770 --> 00:33:54.610
the war against Germany.

00:33:54.610 --> 00:34:00.484
You can win any sales war
by recharging yourself.

00:34:00.484 --> 00:34:01.650
AUDIENCE: Thank you so much.

