00:34:18.170 --> 00:34:21.060
Something that you said that
really resonated with me

00:34:21.060 --> 00:34:26.600
was that failures are stepping
stones to success, and not

00:34:26.600 --> 00:34:28.250
the opposite of success.

00:34:28.250 --> 00:34:30.590
Could you give an
example of something

00:34:30.590 --> 00:34:33.110
that may have appeared like
a failure in your life,

00:34:33.110 --> 00:34:36.900
but in fact it was just a
step to achieve success?

00:34:36.900 --> 00:34:37.900
ARIANNA HUFFINGTON: Yes.

00:34:37.900 --> 00:34:38.620
Absolutely.

00:34:38.620 --> 00:34:43.610
I mean for example, just to
start with my early years.

00:34:43.610 --> 00:34:47.580
I went to Cambridge and I lived
in London for seven years.

00:34:47.580 --> 00:34:52.639
And I wrote my first
book by accident.

00:34:52.639 --> 00:34:54.750
I didn't want to be a writer.

00:34:54.750 --> 00:34:57.350
I was actually going
to the Kennedy School

00:34:57.350 --> 00:35:00.570
to do a post-graduate
degree in politics,

00:35:00.570 --> 00:35:03.290
when I was asked by a
publisher who had seen me

00:35:03.290 --> 00:35:05.650
on television at
Cambridge debate

00:35:05.650 --> 00:35:06.780
to stop it to write a book.

00:35:06.780 --> 00:35:09.850
So my first book did very well.

00:35:09.850 --> 00:35:11.790
And then I wanted
to write a book

00:35:11.790 --> 00:35:14.800
on the crisis in political
leadership, which

00:35:14.800 --> 00:35:18.340
I wrote by spending--
I subsidized myself

00:35:18.340 --> 00:35:21.790
by spending the money I had
made with my first book.

00:35:21.790 --> 00:35:26.870
And that book was
rejected by 36 publishers.

00:35:26.870 --> 00:35:29.900
And that's a lot of rejections.

00:35:29.900 --> 00:35:33.840
And by rejection
36, I was thinking

00:35:33.840 --> 00:35:36.360
that maybe this was the
wrong career for me.

00:35:36.360 --> 00:35:38.950
That maybe my first
book was a fluke.

00:35:38.950 --> 00:35:43.790
And I was walking down
St. James's Street,

00:35:43.790 --> 00:35:46.260
despondent and then
having run out of money.

00:35:46.260 --> 00:35:49.720
And I saw Barkley's
Bank, and I walked in.

00:35:49.720 --> 00:35:52.790
And armed with nothing
but Greek chutzpah,

00:35:52.790 --> 00:35:57.000
I asked to see the bank manager,
and I asked for an overdraft.

00:35:57.000 --> 00:35:59.590
And for some reason,
he gave it to me.

00:35:59.590 --> 00:36:02.480
I still send him a
Christmas card every year.

00:36:02.480 --> 00:36:07.820
And that's something important
to remember during moments

00:36:07.820 --> 00:36:10.810
of failure, when things
are not working out.

00:36:10.810 --> 00:36:13.370
That we're not alone.

00:36:13.370 --> 00:36:17.430
That it's a little bit
like in fairy tales,

00:36:17.430 --> 00:36:21.780
when the hero or the heroine
is lost in the dark forest.

00:36:21.780 --> 00:36:24.000
And all these helpful
animals come out

00:36:24.000 --> 00:36:25.840
to help them find their way out.

00:36:25.840 --> 00:36:28.250
When in life too, there
are helpful animals

00:36:28.250 --> 00:36:31.350
disguised as human
beings, as bank managers,

00:36:31.350 --> 00:36:32.180
there to help us.

00:36:32.180 --> 00:36:34.580
And that's a very
important way to live life.

00:36:34.580 --> 00:36:36.770
In fact, one of
my favorite quotes

00:36:36.770 --> 00:36:41.490
in "Thrive," which I have
laminated in my wallet,

00:36:41.490 --> 00:36:46.570
is from Rumi, the poet who said,
live life as though everything

00:36:46.570 --> 00:36:49.100
is rigged in your favor.

00:36:49.100 --> 00:36:52.180
So whatever happens, if
we can approach it from,

00:36:52.180 --> 00:36:54.010
this is here to
teach me something.

00:36:54.010 --> 00:36:56.120
In fact, there's an
incredible quote--

00:36:56.120 --> 00:37:00.160
I'm going to give you a Cliff
note, page 118 of the book.

00:37:00.160 --> 00:37:02.720
My favorite long quote-- too
long to read to you now--

00:37:02.720 --> 00:37:06.150
by Marcus Aurelius, who
was a stoic philosopher

00:37:06.150 --> 00:37:07.490
and the Emperor of Rome.

00:37:07.490 --> 00:37:11.190
So the guy had a pretty big job.

00:37:11.190 --> 00:37:13.320
And at the end of each
night, he would go to bed

00:37:13.320 --> 00:37:17.530
and write what became his
famous book, "Meditations."

00:37:17.530 --> 00:37:20.030
And in that book,
and in that quote,

00:37:20.030 --> 00:37:23.260
he talks about how
everything that happens to us

00:37:23.260 --> 00:37:26.310
has hidden blessing
and a hidden purpose.

00:37:26.310 --> 00:37:29.870
And when we look at it that
way, life is transformed.

00:37:29.870 --> 00:37:32.860
Because very often, a lot
of our pain and heartache

00:37:32.860 --> 00:37:35.670
come from our attitude
to what happens to us,

00:37:35.670 --> 00:37:38.897
rather than just from
what happens to us.

00:37:38.897 --> 00:37:39.730
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:37:42.519 --> 00:37:43.310
AUDIENCE: Hi there.

00:37:43.310 --> 00:37:44.030
I'm Mark.

00:37:44.030 --> 00:37:46.450
