00:40:27.590 --> 00:40:29.310
And I thought about that a lot.

00:40:29.310 --> 00:40:32.030
So even at university,
I remember thinking,

00:40:32.030 --> 00:40:33.190
God I'm studying so hard.

00:40:33.190 --> 00:40:35.064
But what if I die
tomorrow, what's the point?

00:40:35.064 --> 00:40:35.930
I"ve missed a day.

00:40:35.930 --> 00:40:38.910
What has driven you,
having that thought?

00:40:38.910 --> 00:40:41.300
What currently drives you
to do all the other things

00:40:41.300 --> 00:40:43.341
that you're doing, knowing
that at the end of it,

00:40:43.341 --> 00:40:47.842
what really matters are love,
people, friendship, et cetera.

00:40:47.842 --> 00:40:49.300
ARIANNA HUFFINGTON:
Great question.

00:40:49.300 --> 00:40:52.270
First of all.

00:40:52.270 --> 00:40:56.040
Having conversations about
that is incredibly important,

00:40:56.040 --> 00:41:02.210
because our culture has
really driven death away

00:41:02.210 --> 00:41:03.170
from our lives.

00:41:03.170 --> 00:41:06.120
And in our Greek
culture, of course,

00:41:06.120 --> 00:41:11.130
Socrates famously used to
say, practice death daily.

00:41:11.130 --> 00:41:13.200
Not our of morbidity,
but because it

00:41:13.200 --> 00:41:15.880
puts everything
else in perspective.

00:41:15.880 --> 00:41:20.170
And now, all over Europe, and
now they've come to the states,

00:41:20.170 --> 00:41:23.430
there are these death
cafes that have come up.

00:41:23.430 --> 00:41:26.780
Where people can get together
and discuss their thoughts

00:41:26.780 --> 00:41:28.710
about death.

00:41:28.710 --> 00:41:33.770
There's another movement
called "Death over Dinner,"

00:41:33.770 --> 00:41:37.300
when people get together, have
dinner, and discuss death.

00:41:37.300 --> 00:41:42.170
And "The Onion," the humorous
magazine in the States

00:41:42.170 --> 00:41:43.850
had a feature on death recently.

00:41:43.850 --> 00:41:52.360
And the headline was, "Death
Rate Holds Steady at 100%."

00:41:52.360 --> 00:42:00.240
So I think having that
realization and consciousness

00:42:00.240 --> 00:42:04.810
then means that you really want
to focus on the things that

00:42:04.810 --> 00:42:07.220
can make the most difference.

00:42:07.220 --> 00:42:11.960
And for me, one of the
reasons why I love speaking,

00:42:11.960 --> 00:42:16.120
say here to you about this,
is because I love the thought

00:42:16.120 --> 00:42:22.480
that if enough of
us begin to bring

00:42:22.480 --> 00:42:25.550
these changes into our
lives, we are going to really

00:42:25.550 --> 00:42:28.370
very quickly reach
a critical mass.

00:42:28.370 --> 00:42:31.000
And for those of you with
a scientific background

00:42:31.000 --> 00:42:32.770
here, you know
that critical mass

00:42:32.770 --> 00:42:37.440
is when there's enough
radioactive material

00:42:37.440 --> 00:42:40.710
for the change to
become self sustaining.

00:42:40.710 --> 00:42:42.020
So that's what we need here.

00:42:42.020 --> 00:42:45.090
It's just enough people
introducing these changes

00:42:45.090 --> 00:42:48.860
in our lives will make
this the new reality.

00:42:48.860 --> 00:42:51.430
Right now we're like in
a period of transition.

00:42:51.430 --> 00:42:54.480
Where there is a
global shift happening.

00:42:54.480 --> 00:42:58.500
Thrive is part of
the global shift.

00:42:58.500 --> 00:43:02.980
But if we can accelerate the
shift, then the current way

00:43:02.980 --> 00:43:07.220
we live-- being hyper-connected
24/7, burning out,

00:43:07.220 --> 00:43:09.660
perpetually stressed,
perpetually anxious,

00:43:09.660 --> 00:43:13.244
is going to be seen
as barbaric And it's

00:43:13.244 --> 00:43:14.660
going to be a
little bit like when

00:43:14.660 --> 00:43:17.900
we moved from the Dark
Ages to the Renaissance,

00:43:17.900 --> 00:43:22.000
when we stopped believing
that the Earth is flat.

00:43:22.000 --> 00:43:24.180
And everything changes.

00:43:24.180 --> 00:43:28.150
And I want to be alive
to see that change.

00:43:28.150 --> 00:43:30.200
I think it's going
to be amazing.

00:43:30.200 --> 00:43:32.830
And it's going to lead
to an incredible amount

00:43:32.830 --> 00:43:38.850
of creativity, go-giving
and at every level,

00:43:38.850 --> 00:43:41.610
we'll be able to deal
with our problems better.

00:43:41.610 --> 00:43:43.260
Including at the
political level.

00:43:43.260 --> 00:43:45.960
I'm speaking this afternoon
at the House of Commons,

00:43:45.960 --> 00:43:47.940
where there's now a
mindfulness movement.

00:43:47.940 --> 00:43:53.520
There are 97 members of
the House of Commons, peers

00:43:53.520 --> 00:43:57.760
and staffers who have weekly
meditation and mindfulness

00:43:57.760 --> 00:43:59.480
courses.

00:43:59.480 --> 00:44:02.410
And if you look
around at the moment,

00:44:02.410 --> 00:44:06.140
you see that our leaders,
most of our leaders,

00:44:06.140 --> 00:44:10.030
are so mired in that
second metric of power,

00:44:10.030 --> 00:44:12.590
that they are not able
to make good decisions,

00:44:12.590 --> 00:44:15.730
because they look at
everything through that filter

00:44:15.730 --> 00:44:20.110
of if this going to help
my reelection or not?

00:44:20.110 --> 00:44:27.010
And not to mention the impact
of burnout on decision making.

00:44:27.010 --> 00:44:30.540
It's so funny, because I was
speaking at the US Embassy.

00:44:30.540 --> 00:44:33.770
And I said something
in my speech

00:44:33.770 --> 00:44:36.002
about nap rooms in the
Embassy, and the Ambassador

00:44:36.002 --> 00:44:37.460
said, that sounds
like a good idea.

00:44:37.460 --> 00:44:38.980
We should do that.

00:44:38.980 --> 00:44:41.340
And there's an article about
it in the Washington Post,

00:44:41.340 --> 00:44:43.520
and the State
Department yesterday

00:44:43.520 --> 00:44:46.830
felt that they had to put
a statement out saying

00:44:46.830 --> 00:44:49.715
that nobody in the State
Department sleeps on the job.

00:44:52.270 --> 00:44:55.100
It just shows how
archaic is our thinking.

00:44:55.100 --> 00:44:59.010
And the spokeswoman said, she
understands the importance

00:44:59.010 --> 00:45:01.760
of achieving work/life balance.

00:45:01.760 --> 00:45:03.640
And one day she aspires to it.

00:45:03.640 --> 00:45:07.372
And so basically,
she used the fact

00:45:07.372 --> 00:45:09.330
that she doesn't have
work/life balance-- which

00:45:09.330 --> 00:45:11.100
I think is a
terrible term, but we

00:45:11.100 --> 00:45:13.490
know what she means--
as a badge of honor.

00:45:13.490 --> 00:45:18.110
Hey, you know, I'm too busy
to worry about these things.

00:45:18.110 --> 00:45:22.290
So this is the kind of thinking
that I want to make obsolete.

00:45:22.290 --> 00:45:28.000
So I want it very soon to
be completely laughed at.

00:45:28.000 --> 00:45:34.360
And I want politicians
who it's found out

00:45:34.360 --> 00:45:38.060
that they have pulled
all nighters to then have

00:45:38.060 --> 00:45:40.190
to do damage control about that.

00:45:40.190 --> 00:45:42.570
Because we can't trust
their decisions as much.

00:45:48.689 --> 00:45:49.480
AUDIENCE: Hi there.

00:45:49.480 --> 00:45:49.980
I'm Zoe.

00:45:49.980 --> 00:45:51.420
I work in the
marketing team here.

00:45:51.420 --> 00:45:52.120
Thank you for coming in.

00:45:52.120 --> 00:45:53.130
It was really inspiring.

00:45:53.130 --> 00:45:53.850
ARIANNA HUFFINGTON: Thank you.

00:45:53.850 --> 00:45:54.800
AUDIENCE: I come
to talks like this,

00:45:54.800 --> 00:45:57.008
and I think I'm going to
change something in my life.

00:45:57.008 --> 00:45:58.990
And then real life
tends to get in the way.

00:45:58.990 --> 00:46:00.970
So I was just wondering,
what are your tips

00:46:00.970 --> 00:46:03.740
that you have about really
sticking to your principles

00:46:03.740 --> 00:46:05.020
and making the change.

00:46:05.020 --> 00:46:06.474
You mentioned the thrive buddy.

00:46:06.474 --> 00:46:08.640
But do you tend to write
things down and review them

00:46:08.640 --> 00:46:09.710
every so often?

00:46:09.710 --> 00:46:11.872
How do you make them stick?

00:46:11.872 --> 00:46:13.830
ARIANNA HUFFINGTON: So
the first thing-- and it

00:46:13.830 --> 00:46:18.480
may sound counter-intuitive
is not to judge yourself

00:46:18.480 --> 00:46:24.380
when we determine to do
something and we don't do it.

00:46:24.380 --> 00:46:27.210
To just say, give
ourselves another chance

00:46:27.210 --> 00:46:28.890
and another chance.

00:46:28.890 --> 00:46:34.530
And to make the changes that
we start with very small.

00:46:34.530 --> 00:46:36.870
Because especially
all these driven

00:46:36.870 --> 00:46:40.150
A types here identify with that.

00:46:40.150 --> 00:46:43.070
If we like something, and
we want to bring the change

00:46:43.070 --> 00:46:46.160
we want to just
make them wholesale.

00:46:46.160 --> 00:46:50.680
And then it becomes much
harder to implement.

00:46:50.680 --> 00:46:53.920
And so just pick
something very manageable.

00:46:53.920 --> 00:46:55.750
Just pick one thing.

00:46:55.750 --> 00:46:57.790
Like I suggest getting
30 more minutes

00:46:57.790 --> 00:47:00.230
sleep than you're getting now.

00:47:00.230 --> 00:47:04.550
Or charging your phone
away from your bedroom.

00:47:04.550 --> 00:47:07.040
Or making a gratitude list.

00:47:07.040 --> 00:47:09.960
I think that's something
which is incredibly helpful.

00:47:09.960 --> 00:47:12.950
And my daughter-- I write
about it in the book--

00:47:12.950 --> 00:47:17.390
got involved in drugs in
her last year at college.

00:47:17.390 --> 00:47:20.170
That was one of the heartbreaks,
the difficult moments

00:47:20.170 --> 00:47:22.150
in my life in the
last two years.

00:47:22.150 --> 00:47:25.204
She's now been sober and
went back and graduated,

00:47:25.204 --> 00:47:25.870
and all is good.

00:47:25.870 --> 00:47:28.760
But one of the things
that helped her a lot

00:47:28.760 --> 00:47:32.590
was making this gratitude list
every night of three things

00:47:32.590 --> 00:47:34.250
she's grateful
for, and sharing it

00:47:34.250 --> 00:47:38.740
with two friends who shared
their lists with her.

00:47:38.740 --> 00:47:41.900
And that begins to
get your mind trained

00:47:41.900 --> 00:47:43.860
to focus on the good things.

00:47:43.860 --> 00:47:49.320
Because we are trained to
focus on the bad things.

00:47:49.320 --> 00:47:52.620
And that had some
survival benefit,

00:47:52.620 --> 00:47:55.730
you now, because if, let's say,
we were pursued by a leopard,

00:47:55.730 --> 00:48:00.070
and we focused on the
rainbow, we would be toast.

00:48:00.070 --> 00:48:04.350
So but now, it's not just
focusing on the real dangers,

00:48:04.350 --> 00:48:07.860
we focus on all those
imaginary dangers.

00:48:07.860 --> 00:48:11.270
So learning to focus on things
that we are grateful for

00:48:11.270 --> 00:48:13.040
is a great exercise for this.

00:48:22.820 --> 00:48:23.810
AUDIENCE: Hi, Arianna.

00:48:23.810 --> 00:48:24.480
Oh, sorry.

00:48:24.480 --> 00:48:24.980
Go ahead.

00:48:27.500 --> 00:48:28.740
Thank you so much for that.

00:48:28.740 --> 00:48:31.610
I'm so pleased
that you mentioned

00:48:31.610 --> 00:48:34.620
the giving side of things,
which I think is so important.

00:48:34.620 --> 00:48:37.530
And I remember many years
ago, a mentor of mine

00:48:37.530 --> 00:48:39.870
saying that you go
through stages in life.

00:48:39.870 --> 00:48:42.380
You start with a learning phase.

00:48:42.380 --> 00:48:44.500
And then and earning
phase, and a serving phase.

00:48:44.500 --> 00:48:47.530
But he said, what if you could
do all three of those things

00:48:47.530 --> 00:48:48.260
at the same time?

00:48:48.260 --> 00:48:50.104
Which is something
I've been trying to do,

00:48:50.104 --> 00:48:51.520
and I do a lot of
charitable work.

00:48:51.520 --> 00:48:54.680
But at Google we
give time to people

00:48:54.680 --> 00:48:57.380
to do serving things,
2 and 1/2 days a year.

00:48:57.380 --> 00:49:02.200
And I was lucky enough to
go to Tanzania for 17 days

00:49:02.200 --> 00:49:04.510
to do a volunteering
project recently.

00:49:04.510 --> 00:49:06.820
Where we helped a rural
village to put a water

00:49:06.820 --> 00:49:08.320
supply into place.

00:49:08.320 --> 00:49:11.422
And it was an important
thing, because the villagers,

00:49:11.422 --> 00:49:12.880
many women and
children are walking

00:49:12.880 --> 00:49:15.510
for six to eight
hours a day to get

00:49:15.510 --> 00:49:19.030
on bucket of not so clean water.

00:49:19.030 --> 00:49:23.230
But I remember being in
the middle of that time

00:49:23.230 --> 00:49:25.940
and thinking, this
isn't a scalable thing.

00:49:25.940 --> 00:49:28.610
And I'm not really designed
to be digging and stuff.

00:49:28.610 --> 00:49:33.610
Why don't I get a Bobcat,
or hire a digger to do this.

00:49:33.610 --> 00:49:36.740
But we then spoke to the
chairman of the village,

00:49:36.740 --> 00:49:38.490
and he said actually,
you know what really

00:49:38.490 --> 00:49:40.950
made the difference to us
was that you were with us,

00:49:40.950 --> 00:49:42.670
you were living
in the community.

00:49:42.670 --> 00:49:45.510
You were working side
by side along with us.

00:49:45.510 --> 00:49:46.830
And that really inspired us.

00:49:46.830 --> 00:49:49.630
I think that the type
of giving that you give,

00:49:49.630 --> 00:49:52.260
not just the money,
but your time

00:49:52.260 --> 00:49:53.430
is quite an important thing.

00:49:53.430 --> 00:49:57.690
But my question is, what
are other organizations

00:49:57.690 --> 00:50:00.160
doing that you see
to really encourage

00:50:00.160 --> 00:50:02.550
the right sort of giving
that really gives you

00:50:02.550 --> 00:50:06.050
a lot of energy and makes
you feel a lot less stress.

00:50:06.050 --> 00:50:07.180
What do you see?

00:50:07.180 --> 00:50:08.940
ARIANNA HUFFINGTON:
So thank you.

00:50:08.940 --> 00:50:10.150
That's a great point.

00:50:10.150 --> 00:50:13.920
I see more and more
companies encouraging giving.

00:50:13.920 --> 00:50:16.600
At the Huffington
Post, we, and at AOL,

00:50:16.600 --> 00:50:20.800
which is our parent
company, we give three

00:50:20.800 --> 00:50:22.610
paid days for volunteering.

00:50:22.610 --> 00:50:27.980
And we match volunteer
contributions up

00:50:27.980 --> 00:50:30.720
to a certain amount.

00:50:30.720 --> 00:50:32.870
You see that happening
more and more

00:50:32.870 --> 00:50:35.270
across the world
in many companies.

00:50:35.270 --> 00:50:37.260
But also, as you
said, it's something

00:50:37.260 --> 00:50:40.340
which we can take up ourselves.

00:50:40.340 --> 00:50:41.600
Whatever our circumstances.

00:50:41.600 --> 00:50:42.950
That is what is so interesting.

00:50:42.950 --> 00:50:46.650
I have a story in the book
of a good friend of mine

00:50:46.650 --> 00:50:49.750
who lost her job during
the financial collapse.

00:50:49.750 --> 00:50:51.700
She had a big job in
investment banking.

00:50:51.700 --> 00:50:53.730
She had never been out of work.

00:50:53.730 --> 00:50:56.430
She was completely
undone by that.

00:50:56.430 --> 00:50:59.110
And then I was talking to
her, and I said, you know,

00:50:59.110 --> 00:51:00.730
this might be a
good time for you

00:51:00.730 --> 00:51:04.240
to volunteer in this place
that is on the border.

00:51:04.240 --> 00:51:06.520
A place for at-risk
children in Los Angeles,

00:51:06.520 --> 00:51:08.060
called "A Place Called Home."

00:51:08.060 --> 00:51:10.450
And she looked at me like
I had lost all empathy

00:51:10.450 --> 00:51:11.820
and compassion.

00:51:11.820 --> 00:51:15.720
And I said, you are going
to be looking for a new job.

00:51:15.720 --> 00:51:18.300
But this is the first time
in your life you have time.

00:51:18.300 --> 00:51:20.650
So you can give a
couple of hours.

00:51:20.650 --> 00:51:21.600
And she did it.

00:51:21.600 --> 00:51:23.650
And it is just transformational.

00:51:23.650 --> 00:51:26.180
She was telling me
how first of all,

00:51:26.180 --> 00:51:29.510
it put her own problems
in perspective.

00:51:29.510 --> 00:51:32.540
She stopped feeling
so sorry for herself.

00:51:32.540 --> 00:51:36.440
I really believe she
got another job faster.

00:51:36.440 --> 00:51:39.300
But also she told me the
story of how every night they

00:51:39.300 --> 00:51:42.860
would do a forgiveness circle.

00:51:42.860 --> 00:51:45.570
And she was part of that circle.

00:51:45.570 --> 00:51:51.180
And she forgave her daughter
for forgetting her birthday.

00:51:51.180 --> 00:51:55.510
And the young woman next
to her forgave her father

00:51:55.510 --> 00:51:58.100
for shooting her mother.

00:51:58.100 --> 00:52:01.580
And that connected her with
a whole world out there.

00:52:01.580 --> 00:52:05.460
Whether it's in Tanzania, where
people have to walk for hours

00:52:05.460 --> 00:52:07.810
to get a bucket of
not very clean water.

00:52:07.810 --> 00:52:10.960
Or whether it's in inner
cities, where people

00:52:10.960 --> 00:52:15.060
are living at the mercy
of drive-by shootings

00:52:15.060 --> 00:52:19.600
and real dangers.

00:52:19.600 --> 00:52:23.690
It takes us away from our own
narcissistic preoccupations,

00:52:23.690 --> 00:52:28.910
and our own questioning our
bodies, and our accents,

00:52:28.910 --> 00:52:33.210
and our clothes, and our
place in the pecking order.

00:52:33.210 --> 00:52:36.860
AUDIENCE: My question if about
awareness about well-being.

00:52:36.860 --> 00:52:39.310
So you mentioned
how to recognize

00:52:39.310 --> 00:52:41.146
your batteries being drained.

00:52:41.146 --> 00:52:42.520
Do you have any
tips around that?

00:52:42.520 --> 00:52:45.530
Because I feel like
most people in this room

00:52:45.530 --> 00:52:48.445
probably tend to think,
I'll go hard for a week.

00:52:48.445 --> 00:52:49.320
And then it'll be OK.

00:52:49.320 --> 00:52:52.090
And the week becomes
a month, and so on.

00:52:52.090 --> 00:52:53.090
ARIANNA HUFFINGTON: Yes.

00:52:53.090 --> 00:52:55.120
Absolutely.

00:52:55.120 --> 00:52:58.090
First of all, what happens
is that the more recharged

00:52:58.090 --> 00:53:02.150
you are, the sharper
your awareness gets.

00:53:02.150 --> 00:53:10.080
So you begin to notice any kind
of departure from the center.

00:53:10.080 --> 00:53:12.430
I was talking to a
pilot friend of mine,

00:53:12.430 --> 00:53:16.390
who said to me that
airplanes fly off course

00:53:16.390 --> 00:53:17.690
most of the time.

00:53:17.690 --> 00:53:19.800
The reason that there
aren't more accidents

00:53:19.800 --> 00:53:22.360
is because they have an
impeccable course correcting

00:53:22.360 --> 00:53:23.610
mechanism.

00:53:23.610 --> 00:53:26.050
So little by little,
your mechanism

00:53:26.050 --> 00:53:29.630
of noticing these things
becomes truly impeccable.

00:53:29.630 --> 00:53:32.410
And it's a matter of
where do you start?

00:53:32.410 --> 00:53:34.810
How recharged are you?

00:53:34.810 --> 00:53:38.640
And I find that the minute
I feel stress rising,

00:53:38.640 --> 00:53:41.820
or tiredness, there are lots
of little keys in the book

00:53:41.820 --> 00:53:42.820
that you can practice.

00:53:42.820 --> 00:53:44.180
One is your breath.

00:53:44.180 --> 00:53:46.440
Your breath is an
incredible recharging tool.

00:53:46.440 --> 00:53:48.210
So wherever you are.

00:53:48.210 --> 00:53:50.520
You can just focus
on your breath.

00:53:50.520 --> 00:53:51.990
Breathing deeper.

00:53:51.990 --> 00:53:53.940
Exhaling deeper.

00:53:53.940 --> 00:53:56.200
Nobody else needs to notice it.

00:53:56.200 --> 00:53:59.712
I do it regularly in
boring board meetings.

00:53:59.712 --> 00:54:01.590
You know, I'm moving
to deep breathing.

00:54:04.860 --> 00:54:11.270
And also the other thing you
can do is, look at your schedule

00:54:11.270 --> 00:54:16.010
immediately, and see is there
anything here that I can drop?

00:54:16.010 --> 00:54:19.230
Is there something
I can do without?

00:54:19.230 --> 00:54:20.990
Is there a meeting
that is one hour

00:54:20.990 --> 00:54:23.320
that I can make half an hour?

00:54:23.320 --> 00:54:29.460
And I try as much as possible
when it's not pouring rain,

00:54:29.460 --> 00:54:32.120
to have walking meetings.

00:54:32.120 --> 00:54:33.620
Especially if it's one on one.

00:54:33.620 --> 00:54:35.886
It's just great to just
go for a walk, which

00:54:35.886 --> 00:54:36.885
is much more recharging.

00:54:41.010 --> 00:54:44.510
Depending on where you
are and what's possible,

00:54:44.510 --> 00:54:47.840
I think our awareness
increases every time we do it.

00:54:47.840 --> 00:54:50.070
It's like building a muscle.

00:54:50.070 --> 00:54:53.190
The more we do it, and the
more we pay attention to it.

00:54:53.190 --> 00:54:56.820
Because now many of us don't
pay attention to it at all.

00:54:56.820 --> 00:54:59.590
I had a young woman
in San Francisco who

00:54:59.590 --> 00:55:01.920
came to me after
my speech and said,

00:55:01.920 --> 00:55:06.120
I don't remember the last
time I was not tired.

00:55:06.120 --> 00:55:08.980
So many of us have
been in that state.

00:55:08.980 --> 00:55:12.170
So it's like building
a new muscle.

00:55:12.170 --> 00:55:15.030
And then it becomes
easier and easier.

00:55:15.030 --> 00:55:17.580
I want to thank you so
much for being here.

00:55:17.580 --> 00:55:21.450
For taking this time out
of your very busy lives.

00:55:21.450 --> 00:55:25.260
And I want to invite you to
continue this conversation

00:55:25.260 --> 00:55:26.500
on the Huffington Post.

00:55:26.500 --> 00:55:28.290
Because I feel
one of the ways we

00:55:28.290 --> 00:55:31.590
can have people bring these
changes in their lives

00:55:31.590 --> 00:55:35.410
without having their own
painful wakeup calls, as I did,

00:55:35.410 --> 00:55:39.360
or worse, is to learn from
the wakeup calls of others,

00:55:39.360 --> 00:55:41.940
and to learn from the
thriving recipes of others.

00:55:41.940 --> 00:55:44.190
So I'm going to give you
my email address, which

00:55:44.190 --> 00:55:49.330
is Arianna-- with one R and
two Ns-- @huffingtonpost.com.

00:55:49.330 --> 00:55:51.750
And if there's anything
you want to write about,

00:55:51.750 --> 00:55:53.290
please send it to me.

00:55:53.290 --> 00:55:57.940
And also we have a campaign we
launched, hashtag how I thrive.

00:55:57.940 --> 00:55:59.940
So if you have anything
you do in your life that

00:55:59.940 --> 00:56:03.040
helps you thrive, share it
with others, because you never

00:56:03.040 --> 00:56:06.950
know who else may be inspired
and may want to do it too.

00:56:06.950 --> 00:56:07.450
Thank you.

00:56:07.450 --> 00:56:09.185
And thank you so much.

00:56:09.185 --> 00:56:10.226
